            <div class="faq-a">Solo Schedule C qualifies under B3-3.2-01 self-employed framework with 2-year personal returns + Form 1084 cash-flow analysis adding back depreciation + business mileage + business use of home + Section 179 + entity non-cash expenses. Bank Statement Non-QM alternative on 12-24 months business bank deposits. P&amp;L Statement Non-QM for established practice. Strategy depends on add-back profile.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">P&amp;L Statement Non-QM vs Bank Statement Non-QM &mdash; which is better for design practice?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For most architect + designer practices, P&amp;L Statement Non-QM is better fit. Design practice typical expense ratio runs 25-40% (vs 50% Bank Statement assumption). CPA-prepared P&amp;L producing lower expense ratio = higher qualifying calculation. Bank Statement Non-QM better fit for practices where 50% expense ratio is conservative. CPA coordination recommends path.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does design-build dual licensure affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Design-build firms operating under both Chapter 481 (architect) + Chapter 489 (contractor) licensure have integrated business structure. Income synthesis spans design fee + construction margin + project management. Multi-source documentation more complex than pure architect or pure contractor practice. Form 1084 entity-level analysis essential. Multi-licensure verification supports continuity narrative.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can my interior design business count for qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; FBAID-licensed interior designers under Chapter 481 Part II qualify under same B3-3.2-01 / B3-3.4-02 frameworks as architects. Practice structure (Schedule C / S-corp / partnership) determines documentation path. Florida Board of Architecture license verification + IIDA / ASID membership documentation common. Same multi-source synthesis approach.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does Florida wealth migration affect architect practice + qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Florida HNW + UHNW migration sustains substantial HNW residential design demand at $5M-$25M+ price tiers. Florida AIA architects experience sustained practice growth + premium project margins. Practice profitability driving partner distribution flows. Stronger income trends support continuity narrative for qualifying. Florida-focused firms experiencing growth advantage over national-scope firms.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does NCARB multi-state license affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">NCARB national certification supports multi-state practice mobility. Architects holding NCARB + multi-state licenses serve clients with multi-state property holdings. Practice continuity narrative includes multi-state license documentation. Multi-state revenue stream stability + practice diversification supports continuity. Florida-licensed architects with NCARB recently relocated from CA/NY/IL bring established practice plus Florida market opportunity.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What if I&rsquo;m a senior partner with current-year K-1 distribution timing issue?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">K-1 distribution timing varies year-to-year tied to firm capital reinvestment cycles + project completion + practice profitability. If current year K-1 is in trough, Asset-Depletion Non-QM fallback on accumulated liquid portfolio commonly resolves. Stairway routinely structures Asset-Depletion qualifying for senior partner-track architects with substantial liquid portfolio from accumulated K-1 distributions.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use Construction-to-Perm for designing my own home?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; AIA-licensed architects designing their own primary residence commonly use Construction-to-Perm (single-close construction + permanent) financing. Self-designed + custom home built by separate FL CGC + CRC + CBC licensed builder. Architect role as designer + project coordinator. Florida construction lien (Ch 713) coordination + construction draws + completion certification + permanent loan conversion all coordinated.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does Florida Building Code expertise affect my practice value?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Florida Building Code expertise is substantial competitive moat for FL-licensed architects given code complexity + HVHZ requirements + post-Surfside structural standards. FL Building Code knowledge depth becomes valuable practice asset supporting premium project work. Stronger practice profitability + partner distribution flows support continuity narrative for mortgage qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does post-Surfside SB 4-D affect architecture practice + qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">SB 4-D milestone inspection + SIRS requirements for buildings 3+ stories drive substantial inspection coordination + remediation design work. Architects + structural engineers handling sustained demand through implementation period. Practice growth opportunity for qualified specialists. Stronger income trends support B3-3.4-02 continuity narrative for partner K-1 qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What credit score do I need as an architect?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Conventional Conforming typically 620-640 minimum; better rates at 740+. Conventional Jumbo typically 700+ with stronger reserves. P&amp;L Statement Non-QM typically 660-680 minimum; competitive pricing at 720+. Asset-Depletion Non-QM typically 700+. Higher scores expand program options + improve pricing. Same general credit profile expectations as other professional borrowers.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How much down payment do I need?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Conventional Conforming: 5% (PMI through 80% LTV), 20% (no PMI). Conventional Jumbo: typically 10-20% depending on loan amount + borrower profile. P&amp;L Statement Non-QM: typically 10-20%. Asset-Depletion Non-QM: typically 10-20%. DSCR Non-QM investor: typically 20-25%. Construction-to-Perm: typically 20% lot + construction value.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can my spouse&rsquo;s W-2 income help me qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; spousal W-2 income synthesized with architect partner-track income produces multi-source qualifying. Both incomes counted toward DTI calculation if both spouses are borrowers. Common for architect borrower with spouse holding corporate W-2 role. Multi-source synthesis combining architect W-2 + bonus + K-1 + spouse W-2 expands qualifying capacity substantially.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How long does architect mortgage qualifying typically take?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Standard timeline 30-45 days from application to closing. Multi-source partnership documentation may extend timeline given partnership agreement + entity-level Form 1084 analysis complexity. Asset-Depletion Non-QM typically 30-40 days. P&amp;L Statement Non-QM typically 30-38 days. Pre-qualification analysis ahead of contract significantly compresses post-contract timeline.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does FL Building Code continuing education affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Continuing education affects license maintenance not directly mortgage qualifying. Active Florida Board of Architecture license (which requires CE compliance) is the qualifying-relevant fact. License continuity (no lapses, no disciplinary action) supports continuity narrative under B3-3.1-01 + B3-3.4-02. CE compliance + AIA membership continuity reinforce practice continuity picture.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a recently-relocated architect from NY/CA. Can I qualify in Florida?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; multi-state architects relocating to Florida use NCARB reciprocity for rapid Florida licensure. For mortgage qualifying, multi-state license documentation + practice tenure history in prior state count toward continuity narrative even though Florida practice may be recent. Multi-source income from continuing prior-state engagements + emerging Florida practice synthesized appropriately.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does DSCR Non-QM work for architect investment property scaling?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">DSCR (Debt Service Coverage Ratio) Non-QM qualifies on property rental income alone: rental income / PITI = DSCR ratio. Standard 1.0-1.25+ required. No personal income documentation. LLC ownership accommodated. Common for HNW partner-track architects building investment portfolio. Portfolio scaling beyond personal qualifying capacity possible.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I cash-out refinance to fund firm capital call or practice acquisition?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; cash-out refinance extracts equity from existing property for use including firm capital call, partnership buy-in, practice acquisition, or office space acquisition. Conventional cash-out + Non-QM cash-out paths available. Common architect partner capital strategy alongside SBA financing + partnership funding mechanisms.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What if I want to design my own custom home and act as my own architect of record?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">AIA-licensed architects commonly act as architect of record on their own residence design. Architect liability + insurance considerations addressed appropriately. Construction-to-Perm financing accommodates with separately FL-licensed builder. Architect role: designer + project coordinator + architect of record. Florida construction lien coordination requires careful documentation through construction phase.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

